            <h4 class="heading-lockup__heading">Bridge the gap between in-person and virtual therapy sessions by weaving a clear human voice throughout the UI</h4>
          </div>

          <div class="heading-lockup__item">
            <h5 class="heading-lockup__subheading">Insight 3</h5>
            <h4 class="heading-lockup__heading">Acknowledge and surface small wins to encourage members to continue on their path to recovery</h4>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p>With these insights in mind, we moved forward with the design and development of our first iteration of the app experience. It consisted of three major parts: an account creation flow for new members via web, a React Native app for members to manage their account and join video sessions, and a Treatment Plan builder for members to keep track of their goals while in the program.</p>

        <p>I was the lead UX and visual designer for the Groups member app experience. Ultimately,  I let the member's psyche inform my decisions around the information architecture and user experience. Through user interviews I heard first-hand accounts of the moments leading up to someone asking for help with their addiction. In those moments, they are sick and in an incredibly vulnerable state. The smallest friction or hurdle could cause them turn their back on getting the care they need. In fact, almost half of all scheduled intake appointments are no-shows. This is why it was crucial that we created a seamless experience that was not only intuitive and easy to use, but also encouraging and supportive.</p>

        <h3 class="article__heading">03. Outcome</h3>

        <p>To help achieve this seamless experience, I made sure to pay close attention to detail within the visual design and UX writing. As you'll see in the mockups below, I took a lot of care in getting the tone, imagery, and overall look and feel to be a cohesive, coherent voice. I did this to show members that a lot of thought went into this experience, and that the team that created this has their best interests at heart. I wanted them to feel taken care of ‚Äì like they are talking with a friend who has no judgement and is there to help. I wanted the app to look and feel and sound human ‚Äì especially since this is a substitute for the in-person experience.</p>

        <p>In addition to these details, I also wanted to hand-hold members through tasks that might feel overwhelming or at times impossible (e.g. uploading urine samples, signing consent forms, and uploading insurance photos). As you will see in the below examples, I did this by creating a wizard pattern that I used throughout the app to guide a member through tasks using positive reinforcement and a streamlined UI. I wanted this experience to be kind  ‚Äì to not just tell them what to do or be a detached computer ‚Äì but to be a partner to them and help them through tasks without shame or judgement.</p>

